Dude, stop that shit right the fuck now.
This is a long journey. Some people, like me, leverage our real-life problem-solving skills as they learn. Others draw from experience. A few can just spin thread from air.
Stress is part of the engine that powers you. Sometimes it drives you to bust a thousand words in two hours. Others, you can write a sentence but two random ideas connect while you're walking through the grocery store.
Creativity is more about learning to capture the thoughts you dismiss than waiting for the lottery of burning inspiration. Does it feel like work at times? Yeah, and when I sit down to write, it's by choice. If I believe in my stories and characters, I'll finish them. To do that, I have to believe in myself. I am the sum and product of my stresses, my fears, my life fuckups, my mediocre days, and the boring bits like liking clean socks.
At some point, I wrote (and failed at times) enough to learn how to step sideways. My day disappears, the character takes over. Can I do that every day? Hell no. I'm lucky to get that two or three days a month. But I've worked hard to get past every self-hating episode; when I'm past that time, I can look back at the truth.
I'm better than when I started, and if I keep writing then I'll keep improving.
You will too, if you dare.
